    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-10-05T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-10-05T07:00:00-05:00" n="892"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d892">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 <gloss target="#t_PA1">PA</gloss>/10–553:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 892<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States High Commissioner for Austria (<persName
                            corresp="#p_TLE1" type="from">Thompson</persName>) to the <gloss
                            type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d892fn1">Repeated to London, Paris, and Moscow.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vienna</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-10-05T13:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 5, 1953—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>866. <persName corresp="#p_GK1">Gruber</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_RJ1"
                        >Raab</persName> informed me that they were satisfied with results Paris
                    visit, although I believe they were disappointed not to obtain firm French
                    commitment for reduction of forces which <pb facs="0706" n="1906"
                        xml:id="pg_1906"/> would have been useful in forthcoming elections in Tyrol.
                        <persName corresp="#p_RJ1">Raab</persName> said French felt withdrawal their
                    forces would “leave a hole.”<note n="2" xml:id="d892fn2">According to a
                        memorandum by <persName>W. K. Scott</persName>, dated Oct. 2, General
                            <persName corresp="#p_GLGAM1">Gruenther</persName> had just been
                        officially informed that French forces in Austria would be withdrawn shortly
                        and stationed in Germany. (763.0221/10–253)</note> I said we also had some
                    concern about this. <persName corresp="#p_RJ1">Raab</persName> replied that
                    French could keep 10 battalions in Austria without difficulty if they would put
                    them in barracks which are available and give up the housing which causes so
                    much political difficulty. <persName corresp="#p_GK1">Gruber</persName> earlier
                    informed me French contemplate keeping about 400 men in Vienna and 1 battalion
                    in Tyrol.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GK1">Gruber</persName> said there was some discussion,
                    apparently inconclusive, of problems raised for Austria by steel and coal
                    community. <persName corresp="#p_GK1">Gruber</persName> said his personal view
                    was that Austria should endeavor conclude agreement with each member government
                    giving Austria benefits of plan while secretly undertaking to carry out the
                    responsibilities and duties involved.<note n="3" xml:id="d892fn3">A handwritten
                        notation by <persName corresp="#p_AHG1">Hugh G. Appling</persName> at this
                        point on the source text reads as follows: “Don’t we sometime have to think
                        a little more specifically about how Austria is to fit into the new Western
                        Eur. economy? HA”.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_TLE1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Thompson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
